Insert into Summary (`BookID`,`Summary`) Values ('2641','This work covers the rapid rise and fall of America’s first China factory. Bonnin and Morris established their china factory in 1770; two years later it had closed. Insufficient capital was part of the problem but the author postulates that the factory’s demise was also related to price cutting by the East India Company, a major supplier of chinaware (as well as other goods) to the colonies. The destruction of a local industry by the East India Company only a year before the Tea Act prepared the ground for Pennsylvania’s hostility toward the company in 1773.') ;
